    section
        h2 Research papers
        p From February to June 2023, I helped copyedit an undergraduate student's research into the relationship between #[strong Joan Didion's writing and mental health]. We corresponded via email and swapped drafts. To maintain consistency, I created a style guide that based its guidelines on #[i The Chicago Manual of Style] and #[i Merriam-Webster's Collegiate Dictionary].
        ul
            li.starred #[i Behind the Shades: A Close Look at the Blurred Lines between Joan Didion's Fiction and Nonfiction] (#[a(href='https://platypiduses.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Didion-before.pdf') before] and #[a(href='https://platypiduses.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Didion-after.pdf') after])
            li.starred #[a(href='https://platypiduses.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Didion-style-guide.pdf') Style guide]
    section
        h2 Class editing assignments
        p Yes, I know, I know: it's embarrassing to rely on schoolwork as the basis for potential employment. But these assignments simulate real-world editing circumstances, from marginalia to cordial correspondences.
        p And, most importantly, these show that, yes, I can edit by hand; #[strong I know the typical copyediting marks, for clients who prefer pens over keyboards.] I haven't met many of you like this, but I'm sure you're out there somewhere.
        ul
            li.starred #[a(href='https://platypiduses.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/Class-public-radio-editing.pdf') Radio]
            li.starred #[a(href='https://platypiduses.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/Class-Today-Im-Yours-editing.pdf') "Today I'm Yours"]
